{"104W":{"department":"COMM","number":"104W","title":"Reporting, Writing, and Understanding the News","description":"Techniques of news reporting and writing. The value and role of news in democratic societies. Gateway class to journalism. Prerequisite for all COMM 177/277 classes. Limited enrollment. Preference to COMM majors.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-CE"],"id":112877,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Phillips, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Phillips, C."],"location":"80-115"}],"id":16052}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zacharia, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Zacharia, J."],"location":"260-012"}],"id":15434}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zacharia, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Zacharia, J."],"location":"260-001"}],"id":15698}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"106":{"department":"COMM","number":"106","title":"Communication Research Methods (COMM 206)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 206.) Conceptual and practical concerns underlying commonly used quantitative approaches, including experimental, survey, content analysis, and field research in communication. Pre- or corequisite: STATS 60 or consent of instructor.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci"],"id":112883,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pan, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,true],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pan, J."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":42260}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Vannette, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"9:30:00 AM","instructors":["Vannette, D."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":42829},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":"120-314"}],"id":42825},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":"160-319"}],"id":42313},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":"240-101"}],"id":42314}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"108":{"department":"COMM","number":"108","title":"Media Processes and Effects (COMM 208)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 208.) The process of communication theory construction including a survey of social science paradigms and major theories of communication. Recommended: 1 or PSYCH 1.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci", "WAY-SI"],"id":112886,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"113":{"department":"COMM","number":"113","title":"Computational Methods in the Civic Sphere (COMM 213)","description":"The widespread availability of public data provides a rich opportunity for those who can efficiently filter, interpret, and visualize information. Course develops necessary technical skills for data collection, analysis, and publication, including data mining and web visualization, with a focus on civic affairs and government accountability. Open to all majors and a range of technical skill levels. Involves tackling new tools and technical concepts in the pursuit of engaging, public-facing projects. (Graduate students enroll in 213). Prerequisite COMM 273D, CS 106A, or CS 106B.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":215763,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"location":"160-322"}],"id":43108}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"116":{"department":"COMM","number":"116","title":"Journalism Law (COMM 216)","description":"(Graduate students register for 216.) Laws and regulation impacting journalists. Topics include libel, privacy, news gathering, protection sources, fair trial and free press, theories of the First Amendment, and broadcast regulation. Prerequisite: Journalism M.A. student or advanced Communication major.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112896,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Wheaton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Wheaton, J."],"location":"160-317"}],"id":39636}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"120W":{"department":"COMM","number":"120W","title":"Digital Media in Society (AMSTUD 120, COMM 220)","description":"Contemporary debates concerning the social and cultural impact of digital media. Topics include the historical origins of digital media, cultural contexts of their development and use, and influence of digital media on conceptions of self, community, and state. Priority to juniors, seniors, and graduate students. To request a permission number, please email blazzari@stanford.edu. Include your student ID, major, and year.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci", "WAY-SI"],"id":202310,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Abeles, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Zou, S.","Turner, F.","Abeles, A.","Weiland, M."],"location":"McMurtry Building rm 102"}],"id":15377}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Weiland, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Weiland, M."],"location":"260-244"}],"id":31824},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Weiland, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"6:30:00 PM","end":"7:30:00 PM","instructors":["Weiland, M."],"location":"260-244"}],"id":31825},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zou, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Zou, S."],"location":"20-21B"}],"id":31822},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Abeles, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Abeles, A."],"location":"20-21B"}],"id":31820},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zou, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Zou, S."],"location":"20-21B"}],"id":31823},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Abeles, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Abeles, A."],"location":"20-21B"}],"id":31821}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"121":{"department":"COMM","number":"121","title":"Behavior and Social Media","description":"This course examines behavioral approaches to understanding social media. The course will begin by discussing the design factors that shape behavior online, considering research in human-computer interaction that reflects and reveals communication practices and contexts. Next, the course will examine the psychological aspects of computer-mediated communication and virtual collaboration, including impression formation and management, deception, audience and social networks. Finally, the course will explore the ways in which human behavior is situated inside of social and institutional structures and cultural formations; and with that in mind, it will examine the complex interactions between behavior, society, and information technology.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":217241,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"122":{"department":"COMM","number":"122","title":"Content Analysis: Studying Communication Artifacts (COMM 222)","description":"An empirical and systematic investigation of documented messages in print, graphical, and audio-visual forms and observed human communication behaviors.  Focuses on the design and execution of content analytic studies, including manifest vs. latent content, measurement issues, reliability and validity assessment, computer text analysis, and traditional human-coder techniques. Prerequisite: junior, senior or grad standing; COMM 106/206 or an equivalent course in basic social science research. Limited enrollment.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":212636,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Voelker, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Voelker, D."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":15255}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"124":{"department":"COMM","number":"124","title":"Digital Deception (COMM 224)","description":"Deception is one of the most significant and pervasive social phenomena of our age. Lies range from the trivial to the very serious, including deception between friends and family, in the workplace, and in security and intelligence contexts. At the same time, information and communication technologies have pervaded almost all aspects of human communication, from everyday technologies that support interpersonal interactions to, such as email and instant messaging, to more sophisticated systems that support organization-level interactions. Given the prevalence of both deception and communication technology in our personal and professional lives, an important set of questions have recently emerged about how humans adapt their deceptive practices to new communication and information technologies, including how communication technology affects the practice of lying and the detection of deception, and whether technology can be used to identify deception.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":217240,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hancock, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Hancock, J."],"location":"160-124"}],"id":46225}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Markowitz, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"9:20:00 AM","instructors":["Markowitz, D."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":58281}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"125":{"department":"COMM","number":"125","title":"Perspectives on American Journalism (AMSTUD 125, COMM 225)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 225.) An examination of the practice of American journalism, focusing on the  political, social, cultural, economic and technological forces that have shaped the U. S. press since the  early 1800s.  Aimed at consumers as well as producers of news, the objective of this course is to provide a framework and vocabulary for judging the value and quality of everyday journalism.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci", "WAY-SI"],"id":112912,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Varma, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Varma, A.","Glasser, T."],"location":"School of Education 128"}],"id":15485}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Varma, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Glasser, T.","Varma, A."],"location":"School of Education 210"}],"id":30292}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"127X":{"department":"COMM","number":"127X","title":"The Ethics of Anonymity (CSRE 127X, ETHICSOC 2)","description":"When is it ethical to conceal your identity or to permit another to remain anonymous?  What is the value to remaining unknown, and what might be the cost? Does anonymity free you to think, act, or be in ways you wouldn't otherwise?  What else might it allow or constrain?  How might your answers differ depending on the circumstances or context?  In this one-unit lunchtime seminar, guest speakers will discuss topics that might include:  anonymous sources in journalism; anonymity online; the history of anonymous authorship and attribution; whistleblowers and confidential informants; anonymous egg or sperm donors and birth parents; anonymity vs. confidentiality for research participants; anonymity and art; technology and anonymity.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":217662,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Elam, H."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Elam, H."],"location":"160-323"}],"id":57727}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"130N":{"department":"COMM","number":"130N","title":"The idea of a free press","description":"Preference to freshmen. An examination of the meaning of freedom of the press, tied to but not bound by various Supreme Court rulings on the scope and purpose of the First Amendment's speech and press clauses. Discussions will include a look at the recent and rapid computerization of communication and what it portends for the future of a free press.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci"],"id":211920,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Glasser, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Glasser, T."],"location":"20-21B"}],"id":46961}]],"primary_type":"Introsem"},
"133":{"department":"COMM","number":"133","title":"Need to Know: The Tension between a Free Press and National Security Decision Making (COMM 233)","description":"This seminar examines the dynamic interaction at the highest levels of government and the media when news coverage of secret national security policy and operations impinges on United States defense, diplomatic and intelligence activities and decision making. A prime example: the torrent of secret NSA programs disclosed by Edward Snowden in newspapers and other media. Students explore attitudes, practices, and actions by the media and the government through a series of case studies and simulations. Former editors, reporters, and government officials appear as guest speakers, including Condoleezza Rice. The goal of the course is to inform students about the vital but often fraught relationship between a free press and the government in a democratic society, especially in the management of national security affairs. For advanced undergraduates and graduate students. Application for enrollment required. The instructor is a former Washington bureau  chief of The New York Times. Email Miles Lichtman (milesl@stanford.edu) to request an application. Completed applications are due by 6pm on March 19, 2016. Early applications welcome.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":213319,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Taubman, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Taubman, P."],"location":"160-315"}],"id":42589}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"135":{"department":"COMM","number":"135","title":"Deliberative Democracy and its Critics (AMSTUD 135, COMM 235, COMM 335, POLISCI 234P, POLISCI 334P)","description":"This course examines the theory and practice of deliberative democracy and engages both in a dialogue with critics. Can a democracy which emphasizes people thinking and talking together on the basis of good information be made practical in the modern age? What kinds of distortions arise when people try to discuss politics or policy together? The course draws on ideas of deliberation from Madison and Mill to Rawls and Habermas as well as criticisms from the jury literature, from the psychology of group processes and from the most recent normative and empirical literature on deliberative forums. Deliberative Polling, its applications, defenders and critics, both normative and empirical, will provide a key case for discussion.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI", "WAY-ER"],"id":212937,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"School of Education 208"},{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"School of Education 313"}],"id":44671}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"137W":{"department":"COMM","number":"137W","title":"The Dialogue of Democracy (AMSTUD 137, COMM 237, POLISCI 232T, POLISCI 332T)","description":"All forms of democracy require some kind of communication so people can be aware of issues and make decisions. This course looks at competing visions of what democracy should be and different notions of the role of dialogue in a democracy. Is it just campaigning or does it include deliberation? Small scale discussions or sound bites on television? Or social media? What is the role of technology in changing our democratic practices, to mobilize, to persuade, to solve public problems? This course will include readings from political theory about democratic ideals - from the American founders to J.S. Mill and the Progressives to Joseph Schumpeter and modern writers skeptical of the public will. It will also include contemporary examinations of the media and the internet to see how those practices are changing and how the ideals can or cannot be realized.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI", "WAY-ER", "GER:EC-EthicReas"],"id":210918,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"200-217"}],"id":45034}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Chen, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Chen, K."],"location":"200-230"}],"id":57774}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"138":{"department":"COMM","number":"138","title":"Deliberative Democracy Practicum: Applying Deliberative Polling (CSRE 38)","description":"In this course, students will work directly on a real-world deliberative democracy project using the method of Deliberative Polling. Students in this course will work in partnership with the Center for Deliberative Democracy at Stanford, a research center devoted to the research in democracy and public opinion around the world. This unique practicum will allow students to work on an actual Deliberative Polling project on campus. In just one quarter, the students will prepare for, implement, and analyze the results for an Deliberative Polling project. This is a unique opportunity that allows students to take part in the entire process of a deliberative democracy project. Through this practicum, students will apply quantitative and qualitative research methods in a local community or local high school and subsequently, analyze the relevant quantitative and qualitative data. Students will explore the underlying challenges and complexities of what it means to actually do community-engaged research in the real world. As such, this course will provide students with skills and experience in research design in deliberative democracy, community and stakeholder engagement, and the practical aspects of working in local communities. This practicum is a collaboration between the Center for Deliberative Democracy, the Bill Lane Center for the American West and the Haas Center for Public Service.nnCDD website: http://cdd.stanford.edunBill Lane Center website: http://west.stanford.edunHass Center website: https://haas.stanford.edu","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":217012,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Siu, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Siu, A."],"location":"260-004"}],"id":46164}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Siu, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Siu, A."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":57548}]],"primary_type":"Practicum"},
"142W":{"department":"COMM","number":"142W","title":"Media Economics (COMM 242)","description":"Uses economics to examine the generation and consumption of information in communication markets. Covers concepts that play a large role in information economics, including public goods, economies of scale, product differentiation, and externalities.  Looks at individuals&iquest; information demands as consumers, producers, audience members, and voters. Topics include economics of Internet, sustainability of accountability journalism, and marketplace of ideas.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":214481,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"143W":{"department":"COMM","number":"143W","title":"Communication Policy and Regulation (COMM 243)","description":"Focuses on the development, implementation, and evaluation of policies affecting communication markets. Policy issues include universal service, digital divide, Internet regulation, intellectual property, privacy, television violence, content diversity, media ownership, antitrust, and impact of news on government accountability. Examines political economy of communication policy and the evolution of policies across time.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":214482,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hamilton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Hamilton, J."],"location":"Encina West 202"}],"id":15913}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Varma, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Varma, A."],"location":"110-114"}],"id":58093}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"152":{"department":"COMM","number":"152","title":"Constitutional Law (COMM 252, POLISCI 126P)","description":"This course covers Supreme Court case law concerning governmental powers, equal protection, and certain fundamental rights. The course investigates the constitutional foundation for democratic participation in the United States, covering topics such as the Fourteenth Amendment's protections against discrimination on grounds of race, gender, and other classifications, as well as the individual rights to voting and intimate association, and an introduction to First Amendment rights of free speech and press. Students will be evaluated on class participation, a midterm moot court with both a written and oral component, and a take-home final exam. Lectures will be twice per week and a discussion section once per week.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":216833,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"157":{"department":"COMM","number":"157","title":"Information Control in Authoritarian Regimes (COMM 257)","description":"Does information help autocrats and dictators stay in power? Or does information help topple authoritarian regimes? This course will examine how authoritarian regimes try to control information through surveillance, propaganda, and censorship, what influences the effectiveness of these information control measures, and how changes in technology (Internet, social media, mobile) affect the dynamics of information control.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":216835,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pan, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pan, J."],"location":"380-380C"}],"id":17695}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katsanevas, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"8:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katsanevas, A."],"location":"160-315"}],"id":31934}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"162":{"department":"COMM","number":"162","title":"Campaigns, Voting, Media, and Elections (COMM 262, POLISCI 120B)","description":"This course examines the theory and practice of American campaigns and elections. First, we will attempt to explain the behavior of the key players -- candidates, parties, journalists, and voters -- in terms of the institutional arrangements and political incentives that confront them. Second, we will use current and recent election campaigns as \"laboratories\" for testing generalizations about campaign strategy and voter behavior. Third, we examine selections from the academic literature dealing with the origins of partisan identity, electoral design, and the immediate effects of campaigns on public opinion, voter turnout, and voter choice.  As well, we'll explore issues of electoral reform and their more long-term consequences for governance and the political process.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci", "WAY-SI"],"id":112965,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"location":"School of Education 128"}],"id":42219}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Blascovich, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Blascovich, G."],"location":"60-118"}],"id":42312},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Blascovich, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Blascovich, G."],"location":"Thornt207"}],"id":42311}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"164":{"department":"COMM","number":"164","title":"The Psychology of Communication About Politics in America (COMM 264, POLISCI 124L, PSYCH 170)","description":"Focus is on how politicians and government learn what Americans want and how the public's preferences shape government action; how surveys measure beliefs, preferences, and experiences; how poll results are criticized and interpreted; how conflict between polls is viewed by the public; how accurate surveys are and when they are accurate; how to conduct survey research to produce accurate measurements; designing questionnaires that people can understand and use comfortably; how question wording can manipulate poll results; corruption in survey research.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":212663,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"location":"200-030"}],"id":42970}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Abeles, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"9:20:00 AM","instructors":["Abeles, A."],"location":""}],"id":44125}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"166":{"department":"COMM","number":"166","title":"Virtual People (COMM 266)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 266.) The concept of virtual people or digital human representations; methods of constructing and using virtual people; methodological approaches to interactions with and among virtual people; and current applications. Viewpoints including popular culture, literature, film, engineering, behavioral science, computer science, and communication.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-SI"],"id":204179,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Bailenson, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Bailenson, J."],"location":"McMurtry Building rm 102"}],"id":42552}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Shriram, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Shriram, K."],"location":"160-314"}],"id":42782},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zou, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Zou, S."],"location":"160-314"}],"id":43221},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zou, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Zou, S."],"location":"100-101K"}],"id":43220},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Crawford, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Crawford, M."],"location":"160-323"}],"id":42572},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Shriram, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Shriram, K."],"location":"100-101K"}],"id":42783},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Crawford, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Crawford, M."],"location":"160-323"}],"id":42573}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"171":{"department":"COMM","number":"171","title":"Moving Pictures: How the Web, Mobile and Tablets are Revolutionizing Video Journalism (COMM 271)","description":"(Graduate students register for 271.)  Examine the emerging role of video journalism across web, tablet and mobile platforms. What are the specific needs of these platforms? How can new reporting tools be integrated to efficiently produce video news content? We'll examine case studies and hear from guest speakers about innovations in video journalism on these platforms. Students will produce video journalism pieces using mobile tools, optimized for viewing on mobile devices. Prerequisite: Journalism MA student or instructor's consent.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-CE"],"id":211589,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":40667}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"172":{"department":"COMM","number":"172","title":"Media Psychology (COMM 272)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 272.) The literature related to psychological processing and the effects of media. Topics: unconscious processing; picture perception; attention and memory; emotion; the physiology of processing media; person perception; pornography; consumer behavior; advanced film and television systems; and differences among reading, watching, and listening.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci", "WAY-SI"],"id":112975,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Reeves, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Reeves, B."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":45754}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"176":{"department":"COMM","number":"176","title":"Advanced Digital Media Production (COMM 276)","description":"In-depth reporting and production using audio, images and video. Focus on an in-depth journalism project with appropriate uses of digital media: audio, photography, graphics, and video. Topics include advanced field techniques and approaches (audio, video, still) and emphasis on creating a non-fiction narrative arc in a multimedia piece of 10-12 minutes. Prerequisite: COMM 275 or consent of instructor","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-CE"],"id":211031,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":41606}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"177A":{"department":"COMM","number":"177A","title":"Computational Journalism (COMM 277A)","description":"Focuses on using data and algorithms to lower the cost of discovering stories or telling stories in more engaging and personalized ways. Project based assignments based on real-world challenges faced in newsrooms. Prior experience in journalism or computational thinking helpful. Prerequisite: Comm 273D, COMM 113/213, or the consent of instructor.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215764,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"location":"50-51P"}],"id":43880}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"177C":{"department":"COMM","number":"177C","title":"Specialized Writing and Reporting: Environmental Journalism (COMM 277C, EARTHSYS 177C, EARTHSYS 277C)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM / EARTHSYS 277C.) A practical, writing-intensive course for science and journalism students that begins with the assumption that you already know how to research and relay the essential facts of almost any environmental story. You will go beyond the basics, both as reporters and storytellers. Learn how to write stories that stand on fact but move like fiction, that have protagonists and antagonists, that create suspense, that reveal character through dialogue and action, and that pay off with resonant finales. Limited enrollment: preference to journalism students and students in the natural and environmental sciences. Prerequisite: COMM 104, EARTHSYS 200 or consent of instructor. Admission by application only, available from thayden@stanford.edu. Applications due Nov. 30, 2015.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":207250,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hawk, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Hawk, S."],"location":"School of Education 210"}],"id":45001}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"177I":{"department":"COMM","number":"177I","title":"Becoming a Watchdog: Investigative Reporting Techniques (COMM 277I)","description":"Graduate students register for COMM 277I.) Learn how to apply an investigative and data mindset to journalism, from understanding how to background an individual or entity using online databases to compiling or combining disparate sets of information in ways that unveil wrongdoing or mismanagement. Focuses on mining texts, tracking associations, and using visualizations. Stories produced apply investigative techniques to beat reporting, breaking news, and long form journalism. Prerequisite: COMM 104W, or consent of instructor","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":211590,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Phillips, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Phillips, C."],"location":""}],"id":43878}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"177S":{"department":"COMM","number":"177S","title":"Specialized Writing and Reporting: Sports Journalism (COMM 277S)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 277S.) Workshop. An examination of American sports writing from the 1920's Golden Age of Sports to present. Students become practitioners of the sports writing craft in an intensive laboratory. Hones journalistic skills such as specialized reporting, interviewing, deadline writing, creation of video projects, and conceptualizing and developing stories for print and online. Prerequisite: 104 or consent of instructor.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-CE"],"id":207120,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pomerantz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Pomerantz, G."],"location":"120-314"}],"id":41105}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"1A":{"department":"COMM","number":"1A","title":"Mass Media, Society, and Democracy (COMM 211)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 211.) Open to non-majors. This course examines the role of the news media in contemporary society, with particular attention to cross-national variation in the relationships between journalists, politicians, and citizens.  We further consider the potentially transforming effects of technology on the media-politics nexus.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["GER:DB-SocSci", "WAY-SI"],"id":112864,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"location":"300-300"}],"id":15480}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Konitzer, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Konitzer, T."],"location":"Lathrop 294"}],"id":31867},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Konitzer, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Konitzer, T."],"location":"Econ 106"}],"id":31866},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kim, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Kim, S."],"location":"120-314"}],"id":31844},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kim, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kim, S."],"location":"200-124"}],"id":31865}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"206":{"department":"COMM","number":"206","title":"Communication Research Methods (COMM 106)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 206.) Conceptual and practical concerns underlying commonly used quantitative approaches, including experimental, survey, content analysis, and field research in communication. Pre- or corequisite: STATS 60 or consent of instructor.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112883,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pan, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,true],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pan, J."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":42261}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"208":{"department":"COMM","number":"208","title":"Media Processes and Effects (COMM 108)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 208.) The process of communication theory construction including a survey of social science paradigms and major theories of communication. Recommended: 1 or PSYCH 1.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112886,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"211":{"department":"COMM","number":"211","title":"Mass Media, Society, and Democracy (COMM 1A)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 211.) Open to non-majors. This course examines the role of the news media in contemporary society, with particular attention to cross-national variation in the relationships between journalists, politicians, and citizens.  We further consider the potentially transforming effects of technology on the media-politics nexus.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112864,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"location":"300-300"}],"id":15482}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"213":{"department":"COMM","number":"213","title":"Computational Methods in the Civic Sphere (COMM 113)","description":"The widespread availability of public data provides a rich opportunity for those who can efficiently filter, interpret, and visualize information. Course develops necessary technical skills for data collection, analysis, and publication, including data mining and web visualization, with a focus on civic affairs and government accountability. Open to all majors and a range of technical skill levels. Involves tackling new tools and technical concepts in the pursuit of engaging, public-facing projects. (Graduate students enroll in 213). Prerequisite COMM 273D, CS 106A, or CS 106B.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":215763,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"location":"160-322"}],"id":43109}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"216":{"department":"COMM","number":"216","title":"Journalism Law (COMM 116)","description":"(Graduate students register for 216.) Laws and regulation impacting journalists. Topics include libel, privacy, news gathering, protection sources, fair trial and free press, theories of the First Amendment, and broadcast regulation. Prerequisite: Journalism M.A. student or advanced Communication major.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112896,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Wheaton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Wheaton, J."],"location":"160-317"}],"id":39637}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"220":{"department":"COMM","number":"220","title":"Digital Media in Society (AMSTUD 120, COMM 120W)","description":"Contemporary debates concerning the social and cultural impact of digital media. Topics include the historical origins of digital media, cultural contexts of their development and use, and influence of digital media on conceptions of self, community, and state. Priority to juniors, seniors, and graduate students. To request a permission number, please email blazzari@stanford.edu. Include your student ID, major, and year.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":202310,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Turner, F."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Turner, F."],"location":"McMurtry Building rm 102"}],"id":15379}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"222":{"department":"COMM","number":"222","title":"Content Analysis: Studying Communication Artifacts (COMM 122)","description":"An empirical and systematic investigation of documented messages in print, graphical, and audio-visual forms and observed human communication behaviors.  Focuses on the design and execution of content analytic studies, including manifest vs. latent content, measurement issues, reliability and validity assessment, computer text analysis, and traditional human-coder techniques. Prerequisite: junior, senior or grad standing; COMM 106/206 or an equivalent course in basic social science research. Limited enrollment.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":212636,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Voelker, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Voelker, D."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":15256}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"224":{"department":"COMM","number":"224","title":"Digital Deception (COMM 124)","description":"Deception is one of the most significant and pervasive social phenomena of our age. Lies range from the trivial to the very serious, including deception between friends and family, in the workplace, and in security and intelligence contexts. At the same time, information and communication technologies have pervaded almost all aspects of human communication, from everyday technologies that support interpersonal interactions to, such as email and instant messaging, to more sophisticated systems that support organization-level interactions. Given the prevalence of both deception and communication technology in our personal and professional lives, an important set of questions have recently emerged about how humans adapt their deceptive practices to new communication and information technologies, including how communication technology affects the practice of lying and the detection of deception, and whether technology can be used to identify deception.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":217240,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hancock, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Hancock, J."],"location":"160-124"}],"id":46226}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"225":{"department":"COMM","number":"225","title":"Perspectives on American Journalism (AMSTUD 125, COMM 125)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 225.) An examination of the practice of American journalism, focusing on the  political, social, cultural, economic and technological forces that have shaped the U. S. press since the  early 1800s.  Aimed at consumers as well as producers of news, the objective of this course is to provide a framework and vocabulary for judging the value and quality of everyday journalism.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112912,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Varma, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Varma, A.","Glasser, T."],"location":"School of Education 128"}],"id":15486}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Varma, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Varma, A.","Glasser, T."],"location":"School of Education 208"}],"id":31049}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"233":{"department":"COMM","number":"233","title":"Need to Know: The Tension between a Free Press and National Security Decision Making (COMM 133)","description":"This seminar examines the dynamic interaction at the highest levels of government and the media when news coverage of secret national security policy and operations impinges on United States defense, diplomatic and intelligence activities and decision making. A prime example: the torrent of secret NSA programs disclosed by Edward Snowden in newspapers and other media. Students explore attitudes, practices, and actions by the media and the government through a series of case studies and simulations. Former editors, reporters, and government officials appear as guest speakers, including Condoleezza Rice. The goal of the course is to inform students about the vital but often fraught relationship between a free press and the government in a democratic society, especially in the management of national security affairs. For advanced undergraduates and graduate students. Application for enrollment required. The instructor is a former Washington bureau  chief of The New York Times. Email Miles Lichtman (milesl@stanford.edu) to request an application. Completed applications are due by 6pm on March 19, 2016. Early applications welcome.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":213319,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Taubman, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Taubman, P."],"location":"160-315"}],"id":42590}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"235":{"department":"COMM","number":"235","title":"Deliberative Democracy and its Critics (AMSTUD 135, COMM 135, COMM 335, POLISCI 234P, POLISCI 334P)","description":"This course examines the theory and practice of deliberative democracy and engages both in a dialogue with critics. Can a democracy which emphasizes people thinking and talking together on the basis of good information be made practical in the modern age? What kinds of distortions arise when people try to discuss politics or policy together? The course draws on ideas of deliberation from Madison and Mill to Rawls and Habermas as well as criticisms from the jury literature, from the psychology of group processes and from the most recent normative and empirical literature on deliberative forums. Deliberative Polling, its applications, defenders and critics, both normative and empirical, will provide a key case for discussion.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":212937,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"School of Education 313"},{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"School of Education 208"}],"id":44672}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"237":{"department":"COMM","number":"237","title":"The Dialogue of Democracy (AMSTUD 137, COMM 137W, POLISCI 232T, POLISCI 332T)","description":"All forms of democracy require some kind of communication so people can be aware of issues and make decisions. This course looks at competing visions of what democracy should be and different notions of the role of dialogue in a democracy. Is it just campaigning or does it include deliberation? Small scale discussions or sound bites on television? Or social media? What is the role of technology in changing our democratic practices, to mobilize, to persuade, to solve public problems? This course will include readings from political theory about democratic ideals - from the American founders to J.S. Mill and the Progressives to Joseph Schumpeter and modern writers skeptical of the public will. It will also include contemporary examinations of the media and the internet to see how those practices are changing and how the ideals can or cannot be realized.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":210918,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"200-217"}],"id":45035}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"242":{"department":"COMM","number":"242","title":"Media Economics (COMM 142W)","description":"Uses economics to examine the generation and consumption of information in communication markets. Covers concepts that play a large role in information economics, including public goods, economies of scale, product differentiation, and externalities.  Looks at individuals&iquest; information demands as consumers, producers, audience members, and voters. Topics include economics of Internet, sustainability of accountability journalism, and marketplace of ideas.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":214481,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"243":{"department":"COMM","number":"243","title":"Communication Policy and Regulation (COMM 143W)","description":"Focuses on the development, implementation, and evaluation of policies affecting communication markets. Policy issues include universal service, digital divide, Internet regulation, intellectual property, privacy, television violence, content diversity, media ownership, antitrust, and impact of news on government accountability. Examines political economy of communication policy and the evolution of policies across time.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":214482,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hamilton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Hamilton, J."],"location":"Encina West 202"}],"id":15914}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"252":{"department":"COMM","number":"252","title":"Constitutional Law (COMM 152, POLISCI 126P)","description":"This course covers Supreme Court case law concerning governmental powers, equal protection, and certain fundamental rights. The course investigates the constitutional foundation for democratic participation in the United States, covering topics such as the Fourteenth Amendment's protections against discrimination on grounds of race, gender, and other classifications, as well as the individual rights to voting and intimate association, and an introduction to First Amendment rights of free speech and press. Students will be evaluated on class participation, a midterm moot court with both a written and oral component, and a take-home final exam. Lectures will be twice per week and a discussion section once per week.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216833,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"257":{"department":"COMM","number":"257","title":"Information Control in Authoritarian Regimes (COMM 157)","description":"Does information help autocrats and dictators stay in power? Or does information help topple authoritarian regimes? This course will examine how authoritarian regimes try to control information through surveillance, propaganda, and censorship, what influences the effectiveness of these information control measures, and how changes in technology (Internet, social media, mobile) affect the dynamics of information control.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":216835,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pan, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pan, J."],"location":"380-380C"}],"id":17697}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"262":{"department":"COMM","number":"262","title":"Campaigns, Voting, Media, and Elections (COMM 162, POLISCI 120B)","description":"This course examines the theory and practice of American campaigns and elections. First, we will attempt to explain the behavior of the key players -- candidates, parties, journalists, and voters -- in terms of the institutional arrangements and political incentives that confront them. Second, we will use current and recent election campaigns as \"laboratories\" for testing generalizations about campaign strategy and voter behavior. Third, we examine selections from the academic literature dealing with the origins of partisan identity, electoral design, and the immediate effects of campaigns on public opinion, voter turnout, and voter choice.  As well, we'll explore issues of electoral reform and their more long-term consequences for governance and the political process.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112965,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Iyengar, S."],"location":"School of Education 128"}],"id":42218}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"264":{"department":"COMM","number":"264","title":"The Psychology of Communication About Politics in America (COMM 164, POLISCI 124L, PSYCH 170)","description":"Focus is on how politicians and government learn what Americans want and how the public's preferences shape government action; how surveys measure beliefs, preferences, and experiences; how poll results are criticized and interpreted; how conflict between polls is viewed by the public; how accurate surveys are and when they are accurate; how to conduct survey research to produce accurate measurements; designing questionnaires that people can understand and use comfortably; how question wording can manipulate poll results; corruption in survey research.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":212663,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"location":"200-030"}],"id":42971}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"266":{"department":"COMM","number":"266","title":"Virtual People (COMM 166)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 266.) The concept of virtual people or digital human representations; methods of constructing and using virtual people; methodological approaches to interactions with and among virtual people; and current applications. Viewpoints including popular culture, literature, film, engineering, behavioral science, computer science, and communication.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":204179,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Bailenson, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Bailenson, J."],"location":"McMurtry Building rm 102"}],"id":42553}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"271":{"department":"COMM","number":"271","title":"Moving Pictures: How the Web, Mobile and Tablets are Revolutionizing Video Journalism (COMM 171)","description":"(Graduate students register for 271.)  Examine the emerging role of video journalism across web, tablet and mobile platforms. What are the specific needs of these platforms? How can new reporting tools be integrated to efficiently produce video news content? We'll examine case studies and hear from guest speakers about innovations in video journalism on these platforms. Students will produce video journalism pieces using mobile tools, optimized for viewing on mobile devices. Prerequisite: Journalism MA student or instructor's consent.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":211589,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":40668}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"272":{"department":"COMM","number":"272","title":"Media Psychology (COMM 172)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 272.) The literature related to psychological processing and the effects of media. Topics: unconscious processing; picture perception; attention and memory; emotion; the physiology of processing media; person perception; pornography; consumer behavior; advanced film and television systems; and differences among reading, watching, and listening.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":112975,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Reeves, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Reeves, B."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":45755}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"273D":{"department":"COMM","number":"273D","title":"Public Affairs Data Journalism I","description":"Even before the ubiquity of Internet access and high-powered computers, public accountability reporting relied on the concerted collection of observations and analytical problem-solving. We study the methods, and the data, used to discover leads and conduct in-depth reporting on public affairs, including election finance and safety regulations. Students gain practical experience with the digital tools and techniques of computer-assisted reporting.  Prerequisite: Journalism M.A. student.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215736,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":17311}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"274D":{"department":"COMM","number":"274D","title":"Public Affairs Data Journalism II","description":"Learn how to find, create and analyze data to tell news stories with public service impact. Uses relational databases, advanced queries, basic statistics, and mapping to analyze data for storytelling. Assignments may include stories, blog posts, and data visualizations, with at least one in-depth project based on data analysis. Prerequisites: COMM 273D or Journalism M.A. student.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215738,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Phillips, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Phillips, C."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":43087}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"275":{"department":"COMM","number":"275","title":"Multimedia Storytelling: Reporting and Production Using Audio, Still Images, and Video","description":"Multimedia assignments coordinated with deadline reporting efforts in COMM 273 from traditional news beats using audio, still photography, and video. Use of digital audio recorders and audio production to leverage voice-over narration, interviews, and natural sound; use of digital still cameras and audio to produce audio slideshows; and the combination of these media with video in post-production with Final Cut Pro. Prerequisite: Journalism M.A. student. Corequisite: COMM 273.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":209530,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":16865}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"276":{"department":"COMM","number":"276","title":"Advanced Digital Media Production (COMM 176)","description":"In-depth reporting and production using audio, images and video. Focus on an in-depth journalism project with appropriate uses of digital media: audio, photography, graphics, and video. Topics include advanced field techniques and approaches (audio, video, still) and emphasis on creating a non-fiction narrative arc in a multimedia piece of 10-12 minutes. Prerequisite: COMM 275 or consent of instructor","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":211031,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":41607}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"277A":{"department":"COMM","number":"277A","title":"Computational Journalism (COMM 177A)","description":"Focuses on using data and algorithms to lower the cost of discovering stories or telling stories in more engaging and personalized ways. Project based assignments based on real-world challenges faced in newsrooms. Prior experience in journalism or computational thinking helpful. Prerequisite: Comm 273D, COMM 113/213, or the consent of instructor.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215764,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"location":"50-51P"}],"id":43881}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"277C":{"department":"COMM","number":"277C","title":"Specialized Writing and Reporting: Environmental Journalism (COMM 177C, EARTHSYS 177C, EARTHSYS 277C)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM / EARTHSYS 277C.) A practical, writing-intensive course for science and journalism students that begins with the assumption that you already know how to research and relay the essential facts of almost any environmental story. You will go beyond the basics, both as reporters and storytellers. Learn how to write stories that stand on fact but move like fiction, that have protagonists and antagonists, that create suspense, that reveal character through dialogue and action, and that pay off with resonant finales. Limited enrollment: preference to journalism students and students in the natural and environmental sciences. Prerequisite: COMM 104, EARTHSYS 200 or consent of instructor. Admission by application only, available from thayden@stanford.edu. Applications due Nov. 30, 2015.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":207250,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hawk, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Hawk, S."],"location":"School of Education 210"}],"id":45002}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"277I":{"department":"COMM","number":"277I","title":"Becoming a Watchdog: Investigative Reporting Techniques (COMM 177I)","description":"Graduate students register for COMM 277I.) Learn how to apply an investigative and data mindset to journalism, from understanding how to background an individual or entity using online databases to compiling or combining disparate sets of information in ways that unveil wrongdoing or mismanagement. Focuses on mining texts, tracking associations, and using visualizations. Stories produced apply investigative techniques to beat reporting, breaking news, and long form journalism. Prerequisite: COMM 104W, or consent of instructor","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":211590,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Phillips, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Phillips, C."],"location":""}],"id":43879}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"277S":{"department":"COMM","number":"277S","title":"Specialized Writing and Reporting: Sports Journalism (COMM 177S)","description":"(Graduate students register for COMM 277S.) Workshop. An examination of American sports writing from the 1920's Golden Age of Sports to present. Students become practitioners of the sports writing craft in an intensive laboratory. Hones journalistic skills such as specialized reporting, interviewing, deadline writing, creation of video projects, and conceptualizing and developing stories for print and online. Prerequisite: 104 or consent of instructor.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":207120,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pomerantz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Pomerantz, G."],"location":"120-314"}],"id":41106}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"279":{"department":"COMM","number":"279","title":"News Reporting & Writing Fundamentals","description":"Learn beat reporting and writing skills including source development, interviewing, and story structure for news and features. Emphasis on developing news judgment, clear writing skills, and an ability to execute stories on deadline. Exercises and assignments mimic a newsroom. Students pursue local beats with a focus on public issues and complement written pieces with relevant data analyses and multimedia components. Prerequisite: Journalism M.A. student. Corequisite: COMM 275.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215741,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Zacharia, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Zacharia, J."],"location":"120-410"}],"id":17313}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"289P":{"department":"COMM","number":"289P","title":"Journalism Thesis","description":"MA thesis course.  Focuses on development of in-depth journalism project, culminating in work of publishable quality.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215796,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Nguyen, D."],"location":""}],"id":43905}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"291":{"department":"COMM","number":"291","title":"Graduate Journalism Seminar","description":"Required of students in the graduate program in Journalism. Forum for current issues in the practice and performance of the press. The seminar frequently features Bay Area Journalists as guest speakers. May be repeated for credit.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":113166,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Migielicz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Migielicz, G.","Zacharia, J."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":34702}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"301":{"department":"COMM","number":"301","title":"Communication Research, Curriculum Development and Pedagogy","description":"Designed to prepare students for teaching and research in the Department of Communication.  Students will be trained in developing curriculum and in pedagogical practices, and will also be exposed to the research programs of various faculty members in the department. Required of all Ph.D. students.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":113179,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Bailenson, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Bailenson, J."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":45798}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"308":{"department":"COMM","number":"308","title":"Graduate Seminar in Political Psychology (POLISCI 324)","description":"For students interested in research in political science, psychology, or communication. Methodological techniques for studying political attitudes and behaviors. May be repeated for credit.","min_units":1,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":205969,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":15477}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":42947}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":43998}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"311":{"department":"COMM","number":"311","title":"Theory of Communication","description":"Basic communication theory for first-year Ph.D. students in the Department of Communication.  Introduction to basic writings and concepts in communication research. The goal is an introduction to issues in the field that are common in communication research.  First half of the class will emphasize classic literature about field organization, history and theory.  Second half will emphasize contemporary theory in areas that students select.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":113183,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Reeves, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Reeves, B."],"location":"60-119"}],"id":16062}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"314":{"department":"COMM","number":"314","title":"Qualitative Social Science Research Methods","description":"Part of the doctoral research methods sequence. Focus is on the logic of qualitative research methods and modes of inquiry relevant to the study of communication and meaning. Prerequisite: Communication Ph.D. student, or consent of instructor.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":202142,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Glasser, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Glasser, T."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":41981}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"317":{"department":"COMM","number":"317","title":"The Philosophy of Social Science","description":"Approaches to social science research and their theoretical presuppositions. Readings from the philosophy of the social sciences. Research design, the role of experiments, and quantitative and qualitative research. Cases from communication and related social sciences. Prerequisite: consent of instructor.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":113189,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"60-118"}],"id":44913}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"318":{"department":"COMM","number":"318","title":"Quantitative Social Science Research Methods","description":"An introduction to a broad range of social science research methods that are widely used in PhD work. Prerequisite: consent of instructor.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":113190,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Krosnick, J."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":16065}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"324":{"department":"COMM","number":"324","title":"Language and Technology","description":"In this course we develop a model of how language reflects social and psychological dynamics in social media and other technologically-mediated contexts. The course lays out the main stages of analyzing language to understand social dynamics, including using theory to identify key discourse features, feature extraction, and classification and prediction. The course will draw on action-oriented language approaches to understand how people use language (e.g., grounding and joint action models), and then build on this approach to understand how discourse features from natural language can be used to answer questions from a wide range of social science questions, and ultimately, to the design of new technologies.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":217239,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hancock, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hancock, J."],"location":"50-52H"}],"id":47323}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"325G":{"department":"COMM","number":"325G","title":"Comparative Studies of News and Journalism","description":"Focus is on topics such as the roles and responsibilities of journalists, news as a genre of popular literature, the nexus between press and state, and journalism's commitment to political participation.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":205138,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Glasser, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Glasser, T."],"location":"School of Education 208"}],"id":45882}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"335":{"department":"COMM","number":"335","title":"Deliberative Democracy and its Critics (AMSTUD 135, COMM 135, COMM 235, POLISCI 234P, POLISCI 334P)","description":"This course examines the theory and practice of deliberative democracy and engages both in a dialogue with critics. Can a democracy which emphasizes people thinking and talking together on the basis of good information be made practical in the modern age? What kinds of distortions arise when people try to discuss politics or policy together? The course draws on ideas of deliberation from Madison and Mill to Rawls and Habermas as well as criticisms from the jury literature, from the psychology of group processes and from the most recent normative and empirical literature on deliberative forums. Deliberative Polling, its applications, defenders and critics, both normative and empirical, will provide a key case for discussion.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":212937,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"School of Education 313"},{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fishkin, J."],"location":"School of Education 208"}],"id":44673}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"339":{"department":"COMM","number":"339","title":"Questionnaire Design for Surveys and Laboratory Experiments: Social and Cognitive Perspectives (POLISCI 421K, PSYCH 231)","description":"The social and psychological processes involved in asking and answering questions via questionnaires for the social sciences; optimizing questionnaire design; open versus closed questions; rating versus ranking; rating scale length and point labeling; acquiescence response bias; don't-know response options; response choice order effects; question order effects; social desirability response bias; attitude and behavior recall; and introspective accounts of the causes of thoughts and actions.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":203329,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"361":{"department":"COMM","number":"361","title":"Regulation of the Political Process (POLISCI 327C)","description":"Combined with LAW 577. This course is intended to give students a basic understanding of the themes in the legal regulation of elections and politics. We will cover all the major Supreme Court cases on topics of voting rights, reapportionment/redistricting, ballot access, regulation of political parties, campaign finance, and the 2000 presidential election controversy. The course pays particular attention to competing political philosophies and empirical assumptions that underlie the Court's reasoning while still focusing on the cases as litigation tools used to serve political ends. Elements used in grading: Class participation and one day take home final exam. (POLISCI 327C; LAW 577)","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":216403,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Persily, N."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:10:00 AM","end":"12:40:00 PM","instructors":["Persily, N."],"location":"Law95"}],"id":46976}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"372G":{"department":"COMM","number":"372G","title":"Seminar in Psychological Processing","description":"Limited to Ph.D. students. Advanced topics. Prerequisite: 272 or consent of instructor.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":113223,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Reeves, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Reeves, B."],"location":"120-452"}],"id":46705}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"382":{"department":"COMM","number":"382","title":"BIG DATA AND CAUSAL INFERENCE","description":"Massive datasets of text, images, video, so-called \"big data,\" are increasingly available for research because of the pervasive adoption of new information communication technologies such as social media. These data represent new opportunities for social science research, but prominent examples of big data and data science bear little resemblance to the research designs of social scientific inquiry for causal inference. In this course, we will harness the power of big data for causal inference by using machine learning and statistical tools on large-scale digital media datasets to answer social science questions of cause and effect. Prerequisite: PhD student or consent of instructor; students should have taken quantitative methods and be willing to learn programming. Familiarity with Python recommended.","min_units":1,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":216836,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pan, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pan, J."],"location":"300-303"}],"id":45157}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"386":{"department":"COMM","number":"386","title":"Media Cultures of the Cold War (ARTHIST 475)","description":"The intersection of politics, aesthetics, and new media technologies in the U.S. between the end of WW II and the fall of the Berlin Wall. Topics include the aesthetics of thinking the unthinkable in the wake of the atom bomb; abstract expressionism and 'modern man' discourse; game theory, cybernetics, and new models of art making; the rise of television, intermedia, and the counterculture; and the continuing influence of the early cold war on contemporary media aesthetics. Readings from primary and secondary sources in art history, communication, and critical theory.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":208552,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Lee, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Lee, P.","Turner, F."],"location":""}],"id":45016}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"}}